Darwin's stat uses -f, not -c, for the format string, and has no format string for the mount point at all. While some macs will have coreutils installed via homebrew, and as such will have gstat available, that won't be the case for all. I expect, unless there's a way to get at the mountpoint on the mac I'm not familiar with, it might be best to revert to the old behavior on such systems, i.e. something like this, perhaps?

```bash
case $OSTYPE in
    darwin*)
        _home="$(dirname "$HOME")"
        _mountcheck () {
            [[ "$PWD" != "/" && "$PWD" != "$_home" ]]
        }
        ;;
    *)
        _mountpoint="`stat -c '%m' \"$PWD\"`"
        _mountcheck () {
            [[ "$PWD" != "$_mountpoint" ]]
        }
        ;;
esac

_files=( $(
    while _mountcheck; do
```

