We've encountered a bug (seems like a pretty small one), and we have a workaround, but I thought it would be worth coming here to mention. Either we're extending Jupyter in ways you would prefer we didn't (in which case, we'd like to know best practices) or perhaps our extension is fine and this is just an FYI about how we are using Jupyter.

This appears to have occurred when we recently migrated to the latest version of Jupyter.  Formerly, I think we were 2-3 version back.  I can find out precise details if it's important.

We inject metadata into notebooks, here's a notebook that was created on an older version of ipython:

```
 {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "_datascience": {
          "keep": true,
          "summary": true
        }
      },
      "source": [
        "### Key Defintion: XXXXX",
        "> We define XXXXX by US County."
      ]
    },
```

We recently upgraded to the latest, and the cells were quietly migrated to look this way:

```
     {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "_datascience": {
          "keep": true,
          "summary": true
        }
      },
      "source": [
        "### Key Defintion: XXXXX"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown"
      },
      "source": [
        "> We define XXXXX by US County."
      ]
    },
```

I think it probably relates to the change in types of cells.  It did break the markdown perfectly well into two separate cells, that part is fine.  But our expectation was that our "metadata" that was injected should have also been copied.

Is this a bug, or should we not be storing additional data in this way?

